---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const title = "How 86 Chaos Works | Restaurant Operations Hub";
const description = "How 86 Chaos helps restaurants start with daily workflows and grow into scheduling, inventory, financials, maintenance, and team communication.";
const ogTitle = "How 86 Chaos Works | Restaurant Operations Hub";
const ogDescription = "How 86 Chaos helps restaurants start with daily workflows and grow into scheduling, inventory, financials, maintenance, and team communication.";
---

<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  page="how"
  canonicalPath="/how-it-works.html"
  ogTitle={ogTitle}
  ogDescription={ogDescription}
>
<main id="main">

    <section class="page-hero compact-hero">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="reveal">
          <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
          <h1>Start with one useful workflow, not a giant setup project.</h1>
          <p class="page-lede">86 Chaos is being tested in a working kitchen by the founder, so setup focuses on what teams can actually use during service. </p>
        <p class="page-lede">Pick the area that hurts most first, such as prep, reminders, 86 alerts, schedules, or ordering. Founder Beta includes free setup help, and the rest can be added gradually as the team gets comfortable.</p>
          <div class="chip-row"><span>Start small</span><span>Free beta setup</span><span>Add more when ready</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="phone-frame reveal delay-1"><img src="assets/prep.webp" alt="86 Chaos prep screen" /></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-head center reveal">
          <p class="eyebrow">Simple rollout</p>
          <h2>A practical path for a real restaurant team.</h2>
          <p>The goal is to start small, prove it helps, and build from there without overwhelming the team.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="timeline detailed-timeline">
          <article class="card reveal"><span>Step 1</span><h3>Choose the pain point</h3><p>Start with prep, reminders, 86 alerts, schedules, ordering, or whichever problem costs the manager the most time.</p></article>
          <article class="card reveal delay-1"><span>Step 2</span><h3>Set up only what you need</h3><p>Founder Beta includes hands-on setup help. Build the smallest useful version of the workflow and test it on a real shift.</p></article>
          <article class="card reveal delay-2"><span>Step 3</span><h3>Make it easy for the team</h3><p>Use simple daily screens and 86Voice commands so staff can update work without stopping to learn a complicated system.</p></article>
          <article class="card reveal delay-3"><span>Step 4</span><h3>Add intelligence gradually</h3><p>Connect inventory, invoices, recipes, waste, events, maintenance, labor, and Manager Brief as the restaurant is ready for more visibility.</p></article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    
    <section class="section voice-capability-section">
      <div class="container split">
        <div class="reveal">
          <p class="eyebrow">Why 86Voice matters in the rollout</p>
          <h2>Voice turns real kitchen speech into app actions.</h2>
          <p>It is one of the biggest adoption tools because it reduces tapping. Staff can keep prep, tasks, reminders, recipes, maintenance, and 86 alerts updated without stopping what they are doing.</p>
          <div class="audit-list"><span>Add prep or tasks by voice.</span><span>Mark work done without hunting for the row.</span><span>Create 86 alerts and ask menu-impact questions.</span><span>Search recipes, Help Center, and screens by name.</span><span>Create reminders, maintenance issues, messages, and burn logs.</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="voice-demo-card panel reveal delay-1"><div class="voice-pulse">86</div><h3>“What needs done?”</h3><div class="voice-result"><span>Open prep items</span><span>Daily/weekly tasks</span><span>Active 86 alerts</span><span>Low stock / maintenance watch</span></div></div>
      </div>
    </section>

    
    
    
    <section class="section ai-first-strip">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-head center reveal">
          <p class="eyebrow">Where AI fits in the day</p>
          <h2>AI helps before, during, and after the rush.</h2>
          <p>The point is not to replace the manager. The point is to make sure the manager sees what matters faster.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid-3">
          <article class="card reveal"><h3>Before service</h3><p>Prep prediction, event supply planning, order drafts, par warnings, and Manager Brief attention items help the day start cleaner.</p></article>
          <article class="card reveal delay-1"><h3>During service</h3><p>86Voice, 86 alerts, Menu Intelligence, status questions, reminders, and Kitchen Command Center help the team react faster.</p></article>
          <article class="card reveal delay-2"><h3>After service</h3><p>Burn/waste analysis, invoice warnings, recipe/menu cost signals, labor visibility, and close notes help owners improve the next day.</p></article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section ai-tools-section">
      <div class="container split">
        <div class="ai-suite-card panel reveal">
          <p class="eyebrow">Useful attention, not more noise</p>
          <h3>Manager Brief brings the important signals forward.</h3>
          <p>Ordering risk, invoice price changes, waste patterns, par issues, event needs, prep pressure, maintenance, and other operational concerns can be summarized for manager review instead of hiding in separate screens.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal delay-1">
          <p class="eyebrow">Manager attention</p>
          <h2>See what needs review before the next problem starts shouting.</h2>
          <p>86 Chaos can turn operational signals into clear Manager Brief items, reviewable recommendations, reports, and alerts, while leaving the final business decision with the manager.</p>
          <a class="button" href="ai-tools.html">Explore AI Tools</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section ai-order-section">
      <div class="container split">
        <div class="ai-order-flow panel reveal">
          <h3>AI ordering turns inventory signals into reviewable drafts.</h3>
          <div class="voice-step"><b>1</b><span>Look at stock, par, pending orders, events, prep, waste, and invoice history.</span></div>
          <div class="voice-step"><b>2</b><span>Build a vendor-grouped AI draft.</span></div>
          <div class="voice-step"><b>3</b><span>Flag price changes, waste issues, and par warnings.</span></div>
          <div class="voice-step"><b>4</b><span>Apply suggestions to the normal Order screen for manager review.</span></div>
        </div>
        <div class="reveal delay-1">
          <p class="eyebrow">From chaos to draft</p>
          <h2>Ordering stops being a memory test.</h2>
          <p>Instead of asking “what do we usually need,” managers can start from a draft that considers actual restaurant signals, then make the final call.</p>
          <a class="button" href="ai-tools.html">See AI + Ordering</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section feature-band">
      <div class="container split">
        <div class="panel reveal" style="padding:16px">
          <p class="eyebrow">Example day</p>
          <h2>What 86 Chaos is doing during the shift.</h2>
          <div class="mini-row"><span>9:30a</span><strong>Prep list opens by station</strong></div>
          <div class="mini-row"><span>10:15a</span><strong>86Voice adds two pans of onions</strong></div>
          <div class="mini-row"><span>11:45a</span><strong>“Out of ribeye” becomes an 86 alert</strong></div>
          <div class="mini-row"><span>2:00p</span><strong>Invoice is scanned and attached to vendor history</strong></div>
          <div class="mini-row"><span>4:30p</span><strong>Fryer issue is logged before dinner rush</strong></div>
          <div class="mini-row"><span>Close</span><strong>Sales, labor, cash variance, and notes are reviewed</strong></div>
        </div>
        <div class="voice-demo-card panel reveal delay-1">
          <div class="voice-pulse">86</div>
          <p class="eyebrow">86Voice in the workflow</p>
          <h3>“Mark tomatoes done.”</h3>
          <div class="voice-result">
            <span>Intent: Complete prep item</span>
            <span>Match: Diced tomatoes • Salad</span>
            <span>Status: Done by kitchen team</span>
          </div>
          <a class="button ghost" href="86voice.html">See 86Voice</a>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    
    <section class="section">
      <div class="container grid-3">
        <article class="card reveal"><div class="icon-mark">Flow</div><h3>Reduce the manager chase</h3><p>Even small daily improvements can make the app worth it: fewer missed prep items, fewer scattered notes, clearer handoffs, better ordering review, and less manager chasing.</p></article>
        <article class="card reveal delay-1"><div class="icon-mark">Waste</div><h3>Make waste visible</h3><p>Burn logs, prep history, invoice records, and 86 alerts turn food-cost leaks into something managers can actually see and fix.</p></article>
        <article class="card reveal delay-2"><div class="icon-mark">Pay</div><h3>Let the app earn its spot</h3><p>When the app saves time and helps tighten inventory, it stops feeling like another subscription and starts acting like a control system.</p></article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="container grid-3">
        <article class="card reveal"><div class="icon-mark">Daily</div><h3>Run the shift</h3><p>Prep, tasks, 86 alerts, reminders, and schedule details keep the day visible to the people doing the work.</p></article>
        <article class="card reveal delay-1"><div class="icon-mark">Kitchen</div><h3>Protect consistency</h3><p>Recipes, specs, yields, station work, and menu-impact notes help the kitchen keep standards from living in one person’s head.</p></article>
        <article class="card reveal delay-2"><div class="icon-mark">Owner</div><h3>See the patterns</h3><p>Invoices, labor, daily close, maintenance, and financial snapshots make repeat problems easier to catch and fix.</p></article>
      </div>
    </section>

  </main>
  <section class="cta-band">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="cta-card">
        <div>
          <span class="eyebrow">Founder Beta</span>
          <h2>Try 86 Chaos free for 90 days.</h2>
          <p>90 days free, no credit card, no purchase required, and free setup during beta. Accepted restaurants help shape the product and receive 50% off the first location for the first paid year.</p>
        </div>
        <a class="button" href="beta.html">Apply Free</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
